I'm trying to set up a Rust project that needs both Linux and Windows targets. I wrote this `build.rs` script to generate the manifest.json for cross-compilation:

```rust
fn main() {
    let target = "x86_64-unknown-linux-musl";
    println!("cargo:rustc-linker=libc.so");
    // ... rest of build logic
}
```
The problem is, I can't tell Cargo to use my custom linker directly. How do I override the default rustc-linker without using a Makefile or other external tools?

Let me give you an analogy that might help here: imagine you're setting up for a specific cooking contest on two different continents. You want to bake the exact same cake recipe (the target) but use a very heavy, slow pot of oil specifically designed for the oven (your custom linker). In your case, `rustc-linker` is like that special pot.

Cargo's default behavior is like baking with standard flour and water—it follows the recipe exactly as written in the original book. But you want to use a different cooking vessel. Here's how to tell Cargo to swap it out:

```rust
fn main() {
    // The trick: tell Cargo what your 'linker' target is, effectively 
    // saying "Hey, this is where I will link everything together"
    let my_target = "x86_64-unknown-linux-musl";
    println!("cargo:rustc-linker={}", my_target);
    println!("cargo:rustc-targets={{...}}"); // Tell Cargo about your target
}
```
The key part is the `println!` with the linker name. It acts like a custom instruction in the recipe book, telling Cargo, "When linking this binary, go to my heavy pot instead of the standard one." This way, you don't need to manually change `rustc-linker` inside your target code or use Makefiles.
